Locality: South Richmond Marshes (Stege, Hoffman) and Meeker Slough
Observation Details: My first CBCH from this location appear to be of barlowi ssp. There is very little available data to  say, which subspecies is rather commonplace in western coastal part of Contra Costa County parts of the Bay Area this is not quite obvious, however, just on the other side of the bay in Marin County's most likely ssp. to be found is "neglectus" , perhaps even "rufescens", on the other hand, just to the south of Richmond, Contra Costa Co, in Alameda county, especially in the southern part, the appearance of barlowi ssp. was already documented. Everything indicates that the western part of Contra Costa County, can be a real boundary zone of occurrence of this two ssp. of Poecile rufescens, to south of this area "barlowi", to north "neglectus". Surprisingly and disappointingly eBird database, however, does not give the option of differentiate among subspecies of  CBCH. It should be added though, that it was a very windy afternoon, and not necessarily this bird truly was confine to this area

Observation Details: The Chestnut-Backed Chickadees are the least skittish of the other 2 species.  They will sit on the tube feeder or in the Dinner Bell feeder and eat there, sometimes for a few minutes or until they are chased off by another bird (usually Red-Breasted Nuthatch or one of their own).  They will not share the Dinner Bell feeder - they will chase any other chickadee away from it. They also like the suet from the tail prop feeder and will sit there for a minute to eat, or take a bite, move to a perch on the feeder pole then back to the suet.  They will eat on the opposite side of the suet feeder from another bird, but will not share their side.  Usually they will fly away if another chickadee or nuthatch lands on their side.  They also eat on the ground under the feeder - nuts discarded from the feeders by the nuthatches or chickadees, fir cones/samara from surrounding trees.  They will spend a few minutes hopping around on the ground feeding unless they are spooked by a Steller's Jay swooping down to the feeder.  They will even continue eating near California Quail who are also cleaning up under the feeder. All of the chickadees call (chick-a-dee-dee-dee) from the elderberry tree before they fly to the feeder, and when they are eating from the branches in the fir tree above the feeders.  They use other calls, twits and chirps, shortened calls (chick-a-dee) on the feeder.  They use single twits, chirps, and whirrs when they and the nuthatches are fighting for space on the feeder pole.  I've also heard those sounds when I'm near the feeder pole and they are impatiently waiting for me to re-fill or clean the feeders, or refill the birdbath.  These will sometimes approach within 2 feet of me when I'm taking care of the birdbath/birdfeeder.

Observation Details: This was not an overcount. There was a single very vocal flock consisting of AT LEAST 12 CBCHs, and I was floored by this find! I've only seen this species on Glass Hill a few times in the nearly 20 years that I've hiked there, and it was always a single bird seen within a winter feeding flock. This group of a dozen (or more) out-of-range Chestnut-backs provides still more evidence that chickadees and nuthatches are  making some surprising elevational movements this season. I would be very surprised if Chestnut-backs (and the other chickadee species), nuthatches, kinglets, and siskins fail to visit La Grande bird feeders once their natural food resources in the forest decline this coming winter. Photos.

Observation Details: My first CBCH from this location appear to be of barlowi ssp. There is very little available data to  say, which subspecies is rather commonplace in western coastal part of Contra Costa County parts of the Bay Area this is not quite obvious, however, just on the other side of the bay in Marin County's most likely ssp. to be found is "neglectus" , perhaps even "rufescens", on the other hand, just to the south of Richmond, Contra Costa Co, in Alameda county, especially in the southern part, the appearance of barlowi ssp. was already documented. Everything indicates that the western part of Contra Costa County, can be a real boundary zone of occurrence of this two ssp. of Poecile rufescens, to south of this area "barlowi", to north "neglectus". Surprisingly and disappointingly eBird database, however, does not give the option of differentiate among subspecies of  CBCH. It should be added though, that it was a very windy afternoon, and not necessarily this bird truly was confine to this area

Observation Details: This was not an overcount. There was a single very vocal flock consisting of AT LEAST 12 CBCHs, and I was floored by this find! I've only seen this species on Glass Hill a few times in the nearly 20 years that I've hiked there, and it was always a single bird seen within a winter feeding flock. This group of a dozen (or more) out-of-range Chestnut-backs provides still more evidence that chickadees and nuthatches are  making some surprising elevational movements this season. I would be very surprised if Chestnut-backs (and the other chickadee species), nuthatches, kinglets, and siskins fail to visit La Grande bird feeders once their natural food resources in the forest decline this coming winter. Observation Details: Found near the parking lot for the FA3 wheel chair trail, here: (38.5173232, -122.0590734). Heard calling by all three of us and recognized as a likely chickadee, it then popped up in some bare branches and gave us great looks and photos. Shortly after the bird flew off and despite some brief effort we were unable to relocate the bird. It seemed to be moving upstream. This was around 10am. Typical chickadee face pattern with black head and throat, white cheek, grayish underparts. Rich chestnut on the back and this individual had extensive chestnut color on the flanks, consistent with the more northerly ssp. County bird for Cam and Julian! Photos to be added.

Observation Details: My first CBCH from this location appear to be of barlowi ssp. There is very little available data to  say, which subspecies is rather commonplace in western coastal part of Contra Costa County parts of the Bay Area this is not quite obvious, however, just on the other side of the bay in Marin County's most likely ssp. to be found is "neglectus" , perhaps even "rufescens", on the other hand, just to the south of Richmond, Contra Costa Co, in Alameda county, especially in the southern part, the appearance of barlowi ssp. was already documented. Everything indicates that the western part of Contra Costa County, can be a real boundary zone of occurrence of this two ssp. of Poecile rufescens, to south of this area "barlowi", to north "neglectus". Surprisingly and disappointingly eBird database, however, does not give the option of differentiate among subspecies of  CBCH. It should be added though, that it was a very windy afternoon, and not necessarily this bird truly was confine to this area

Observation Details: Updated:  Originally thought this was a hybrid, but consensus is that pollen accounts for the yellow belly observed on this particular bird. Spotted what appears to be a rare hybrid: Chestnut-backed chickadee x Yellow-bellied tit (hybrid).  Distinguishing features of a Chestnut backed, but with a very bright yellow belly! (*on par with the yellow coloring of an immature/non-breeding male American Goldfinch …or the yellow on a Cedar Waxwing for perspective comparison of the yellow hue/tone observed).  The yellow coloring was so unusual, vibrant and notable that I’ve spent the past week researching both my photos and ornithology sources and believe that this is at the least a Chestnut-backed chickadee hybrid of some sort….with my inclination that it’s a hybrid related to the Yellow-bellied tit.  I was able to spend an exclusive 15 or so minutes observing this bird and will include a handful of photos to accompany this species account.  Photos are the best I could capture in the moment with my iPhone, etc.
